00:33:02.440 --> 00:33:05.640
From what people have said
on Twitter and things,

00:33:05.640 --> 00:33:09.360
I think there are cultural
difficulties with building

00:33:09.360 --> 00:33:11.240
relationships in the US.

00:33:11.240 --> 00:33:14.680
And there is that distance, the
doctor wearing the white coat

00:33:14.680 --> 00:33:18.970
and being the person
who is in power.

00:33:18.970 --> 00:33:20.622
You know, in the
powerful situation.

00:33:20.622 --> 00:33:23.800
AUDIENCE: Yeah, thanks so
much for coming and sharing

00:33:23.800 --> 00:33:24.675
your story.

00:33:24.675 --> 00:33:27.780
It was very inspirational.

00:33:27.780 --> 00:33:29.900
So I think my question
is somewhat related

00:33:29.900 --> 00:33:33.530
to the last question, which
was-- you mentioned that

00:33:33.530 --> 00:33:36.620
even though the campaign is
slowly but surely picking up

00:33:36.620 --> 00:33:39.520
steam here in the States.

00:33:39.520 --> 00:33:41.990
I guess, what are
some of the barriers

00:33:41.990 --> 00:33:44.930
that you're coming across
that-- I mean, maybe

00:33:44.930 --> 00:33:45.730
even not barriers.

00:33:45.730 --> 00:33:48.870
But you know, what
sort of factors

00:33:48.870 --> 00:33:54.750
are making it slower to come
to shape here in the US?

00:33:54.750 --> 00:33:57.130
And maybe, how can
we, as Googlers,

00:33:57.130 --> 00:34:01.390
and how can the viewers help
sort of pick up that steam here

00:34:01.390 --> 00:34:02.190
in the States?

00:34:02.190 --> 00:34:04.410
KATE GRANGER: So I think
one of the barriers

00:34:04.410 --> 00:34:08.710
that people often talk about
is "we do that already."

00:34:08.710 --> 00:34:11.250
We don't need to be told
something so obvious

00:34:11.250 --> 00:34:13.489
as that because we
do that already.

00:34:13.489 --> 00:34:18.409
Now, I think if you went and
looked, videoed every health

00:34:18.409 --> 00:34:21.860
care interaction that a
doctor has with a patient,

00:34:21.860 --> 00:34:23.999
they wouldn't necessarily
introduce themselves

00:34:23.999 --> 00:34:24.540
all the time.

00:34:24.540 --> 00:34:27.500
They just think they do.

00:34:27.500 --> 00:34:30.880
And I think that
sort of arrogance

00:34:30.880 --> 00:34:35.920
almost is really a very
big barrier in this.

00:34:35.920 --> 00:34:39.159
We have a campaign in
the UK called the 6 C's,

00:34:39.159 --> 00:34:41.120
which is for nurses.

00:34:41.120 --> 00:34:45.239
And it's like Commitment
Compassion, Courage Competence,

00:34:45.239 --> 00:34:47.900
the things that you need
to be a really good nurse.

00:34:47.900 --> 00:34:52.389
And that got criticised as
well for being too simplistic.

00:34:52.389 --> 00:34:54.340
We don't need to be
told these things.

00:34:54.340 --> 00:34:56.290
But actually, we do.

00:34:56.290 --> 00:34:59.070
We need to go back
to the basics of care

00:34:59.070 --> 00:35:02.820
and really sort of foster
those relationships.

00:35:02.820 --> 00:35:05.220
And then we can worry about
all the complicated things

00:35:05.220 --> 00:35:07.600
that come after.

00:35:07.600 --> 00:35:10.470
So in terms of what
Googlers could do,

00:35:10.470 --> 00:35:12.900
I think it's all about
spreading a message.

00:35:12.900 --> 00:35:16.620
So you're in a very powerful
social media presence

00:35:16.620 --> 00:35:20.530
in the global setting, really.

00:35:20.530 --> 00:35:23.700
And I think anything
anybody can do

00:35:23.700 --> 00:35:27.130
to spread this message
is really important.

00:35:27.130 --> 00:35:29.170
We're all patients at
times in our lives.

00:35:29.170 --> 00:35:32.965
Our children are patients.

00:35:32.965 --> 00:35:36.100
Our elderly relatives
are patients.

00:35:36.100 --> 00:35:38.962
And we all come into
contact with health care

00:35:38.962 --> 00:35:39.670
during our lives.

00:35:39.670 --> 00:35:43.790
And the experience of that has
to be better than it is now.

00:35:43.790 --> 00:35:44.790
